title.en: Ontology for Named Entity Representation in Scholarly Publications (OnNER)

description.en: OnNER is designed to capture and represent named entities — terms identified and labeled using named entity recognition (NER) methods — along with relevant semantic context, such as their location within a document, from scholarly publications. The ontology is aligned with Basic Formal Ontology (BFO) and Information Artifact Ontology (IAO), and it also incorporates relevant high-level concepts from Relation Ontology (RO), Ontology for Biomedical Investigations (OBI), and NCBI organismal classification (NCBITaxon).

title.value: Ontology for Named Entity Representation in Scholarly Publications (OnNER)

definition.value: A word or group of words within a scholarly publication that has been identified and classified as a named entity.
A system that automates the process of identifying and categorizing named entities within text.
Text accompanying another item, such as a picture.
A concept assigned to a named entity to classify it within a particular context.

example.value: Within the cellulose domain, the term "nanoparticle shape" is classified with the label "Property".

definition.value: A specialized piece of text representing mathematical expressions, chemical formulas, etc., and can appear within either a paragraph or a caption.

example.value: The chemical formula of sodium hydroxide and sodium chloride are NaOH and NaCl respectively.

definition.value: A piece of text defined by a start point and an end point.
A status indicating that the corresponding term has been reviewed by domain experts and proposed either a different label or a revised span, particularly if the term comprises multiple words.
A named entity consisting of one or more words identified by a single classification label, with different parts of the named entity identified with distinct classification labels.

example.value: The term "nanoparticle shape" (classified as "material") could be seen as a nested named entity consisting of "nanoparticle" (classified as "structure") and "shape" (classified as "property"), both of which are individual named entities.

definition.value: A special fragment of text that typically appears with the abstract and may contain one or more labeled terms.
A status indicating that the corresponding term has not yet been reviewed by domain experts to determine its inclusion in the domain ontology.
A primary element for organizing the main text within publications, capable of being nested and accommodating various other document parts like paragraphs and formulas.
A document part that does not rely on the sequential order of appearing within a publication for semantic significance.
A brief overview of a scholarly publication typically positioned at the beginning of a document, diverging from the usual flow of the document's text.
An information content entity that is part of a document.
A summary of the entire document that is substantially smaller than the document it summarizes. It is about the document it summarizes.
A marker that denotes the explicit conclusion of the main text.
An individual human being.
A collection of information content entities intended to be understood together as a whole.

A collection of bibliographic records, each of which references a publication (or a work in preparation for publication). Examples of bibliographic collections include a collection of the bibliographic records of all the publications that a single individual has authored, or a collection of those bibliographic records to be included in a research paper, where they are expressed as a reference list.
A detailed information of the source of a cited work that helps to locate the original content on the web.
A logical division of the text, usually numbered and/or titled, which may contain subsections.

A brief summary of a book, a research article, thesis, review, conference proceeding or any in-depth analysis of a particular subject or discipline, the purpose of which is to help the reader quickly ascertain the publication's purpose.
A labeling schema consists of a unique set of labels customized for a particular domain or purpose.

example.value: The "Material," "Property," and "Process" labels are part of the CelloGraph schema, designed specifically for the cellulose domain.

definition.value: A named entity consisting of one or more words identified by a single classification label.

example.value: The term "modulation" could be identified and labeled as a "process" within the cellulose domain.

definition.value: A document part that relies on the sequential order of appearing within a publication for semantic significance.
A structured entity formed by a group of individuals or legal entities with a common purpose.
A caption distinguishes itself from a paragraph by being a component of a floating document part, such as a table or figure, where it provides a description of the respective element.
A floating document element that has the flexibility to be positioned anywhere within a publication.
An essential role to identify and classify named entities within text.
A collection of bibliographic references typically appears at the end of a document

A subclass of FRBR expression, restricted to expressions of fabio:Works. For your latest research paper, the preprint submitted to the publisher, and the final published version to which the publisher assigned a unique digital object identifier, are both expressions of the same work.
Structural components of scholarly publications that assist in locating named entities.

comment.en: A status is associated with each term in the ontology to signify its current state within the system.

definition.value: A self-contained unit of discourse that deals with a particular point or idea. Paragraphs contains one or more sentences. The start of a paragraph is indicated by beginning on a new line, which may be indented or separated by a small vertical space by the preceding paragraph.
A piece of text, often comprising one or more sentences, that can be found both within and outside of a section and its beginning indicates the start of a new line in the text.

A realizable entity the manifestation of which brings about some result or end that is not essential to a continuant in virtue of the kind of thing that it is but that can be served or participated in by that kind of continuant in some kinds of natural, social or institutional contexts.
A unit of information expressed in mathematical, chemical or logical symbols and language.
A semantically meaningful pieces of text, such as keywords, paragraphs, and labeled terms (also known as named entities), within a publication.
A status indicating that the corresponding term has been reviewed by domain experts and deemed ineligible for inclusion in the domain ontology.

A record that uniquely describes a particular textual or data publication (or a work in preparation for publication). Each bibliographic record is a set of entities describing aspects of the referenced work, including, for example, but not restricted to: authors, title, journal, publication year, DOI, ISSN, publisher and copyright information, or, in the case of a data publication: creators, title, version, archive, publication year, DOI or other identifier). The FRBR expression of a bibliographic record is a bibliographic reference, which usually contains only a sub-set of these entities, ordered in a particular way that corresponds to the house style of the publication in which it occurs.
A communication object comprising one or more graphics, drawings, images, or other visual representations.
A floating document element that has the flexibility to be positioned anywhere within a publication.
A role inhering in a human being or an organization or an aggregate of any of the aforementioned that is realized by the bearer being the agent in a document act.
A floating document element that has the flexibility to be positioned anywhere within a publication.
A unique document format that showcases original research or academic discoveries.
A set of data arranged in cells within rows and columns.
An essential role to act as an author.
A status indicating that the corresponding term has been reviewed by domain experts and determined its inclusion in the domain ontology.
The specific date and time when a particular status is officially assigned to a labeled term (also known as a named entity).
The corresponding text for a schema name.
A unique identification number of a listing within a document.
The relationship between a floating document element (e.g., a figure, a table, or a listing) and a text fragment (e.g., a paragraph, a caption, or a formula).

definition.value: A text segment of a label.
The number of characters in a labeled term.
The relationship between a detailed source information (e.g., a bibliographic reference) that helps to locate the content of a cited work on the web and a text fragment citing someone else's work.
A content of a paragraph.
A place where an organization is physically located.
The relationship between a person who holds a publication author role and a document (e.g., a scholarly publication) that a person has written.
The relationship between a directly contained entity (e.g., a document part) and a container entity (e.g., a document or a scholarly publication).
A text segment of a labeled term.
The relationship between a system (e.g., NER system) and its designated owner or operator.
The relationship of one ordered document element (e.g., a section or a paragraph) with another ordered document element.
The relationship between a container entity (e.g., a bibliography) and a detailed source information (e.g., a bibliographic reference) that helps to locate the content of a cited work on the web.

The relationship between a classification category (e.g., a label) of a labeled term (also known as a named entity) and a domain-specific schema where a classification category belongs to (e.g., a labeling schema).
The relationship between a status of a labeled term (also known as a named entity) and an entity (e.g., a person or an NER system) privileged with a NER labeler role.
The relationship between a document (e.g., a scholarly publication) and a detailed source information (e.g., a bibliographic reference) that helps to locate the content of a cited work on the web.

definition.value: A unique identification number of a figure within a document.
A date when a particular publication was made publicly available or officially released to the audience.
The relationship between a text fragment citing someone else's work and a detailed source information (e.g., a bibliographic reference) that helps to locate the content of a cited work on the web.
The relationship between an entity (e.g., a person or an NER system) privileged with a NER labeler role and a status of a labeled term (also known as a named entity).
The relationship between a role (e.g., a publication author role) that identifies a person as an author of a publication and a person.
The relationship between a person and a role (e.g., a publication author role) that identifies a person as an author of a publication.

The citing entity cites the cited entity, either directly and explicitly (as in the reference list of a journal article), indirectly (e.g. by citing a more recent paper by the same group on the same topic), or implicitly (e.g. as in artistic quotations or parodies, or in cases of plagiarism).
A unique identification of an online document.
A name by which an organization is formally known and identified.
A text segment of a keyword.
The relationship between a person and an organization where a person is affiliated with.
The relationship between a labeled term (also known as a named entity) and a status of a labeled term.
The relationship between a contained entity (e.g., a document part), regardless of its direct or indirect containment and a container entity (e.g., a document or a scholarly publication).
The relationship between a contained entity (e.g., a document part), regardless of its direct or indirect containment and a container entity (e.g., a document or a scholarly publication).
The version number of the NER system used for named entity recognition.
The relationship between a status of a labeled term (also known as a named entity) and a classification category (e.g., a label) of a labeled term.
The title of a publication.
The position of a section whithin a publication.
The relationship between a text fragment (e.g., a paragraph, a caption, or a formula) and a floating document element (e.g., a figure, a table, or a listing).
